					<hr size="1" noshade />
					<div class="commentheading">On December 09, 2006 at 06:56 PM, Michael Chu said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>Re: 4&quot; mini cheesecakes</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody"><div class='commentquote'>Robin wrote:<div class='commentquotebody'>Hello, I am trying to make this cheescake in the mini version (4" springform")because I can't afford to give everyone in my family a 10" cheescake.  How would I adjust the time for cooking?  Also, I thought the grahm cracker crust was suppose to come up the side a bit is this not so?</div></div><br />
I've never made a 4-in. cheesecake. I would suggest a trial run first - bake for 10 min. at 500&#176;F and then lower the temperature to 200&#176;F just like the original recipe. Instead of baking for over 1-1/2 hour, bake for 30 minutes and then check on doneness every 5 minutes. That will give you a ballpark figure for how long it will take to bake the rest of the cheesecakes. (I'm guessing it will take 40 min. at 200&#176;F.)<br />
<br />
In a springform pan, graham cracker crusts are generally formed on the bottom only. If a side crust is desired, that is often pressed onto the sides by hand.</div>
