					<hr size="1" noshade />
					<div class="commentheading">On March 19, 2010 at 08:30 PM, Dilbert said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject"></div>
					<div class="commentbody">in the grand scheme of things, there's two 'types' of cheesecakes -<br />
<br />
one is very dense<br />
one is more fluffy<br />
<br />
the fluffy bit is usually beaten more vigorously to introduce air into the filling 'batter'<br />
<br />
the air heats, expands, things puff up.  <br />
puffing up more at the edges is indicative of too high a bake temp - the 'outside' of the cake is heating up faster than the 'middle'<br />
<br />
the difficulties controlling the low bake temps you mention could be the basis of the problem.<br />
<br />
'fixing' the oven could be a bit on the tricky side.  <br />
one classic approach to creating an even bake is a bain-marie - the water bath helps even out the temps of the baking pan.<br />
<br />
just be sure the pan does not let water from the bain-marie seep into the cheese cake crust . . .</div>
					<hr size="1" noshade />
				
